<article>
    <h1>In&#xAD;dia re&#xAD;ports record daily jump in cases yet again</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200913/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-13"><time>2020-09-13</time></a>
        - <span>TOP OF THE NEWS</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>•</p>
    <p>NEW DELHI In­dia re­ported a record daily jump in coro­n­avirus cases for the sec­ond con­sec­u­tive day, log­ging 97,570 new in­fec­tions yes­ter­day, data from the Health Min­istry showed.</p>
    <p>With to­tal cases at more than 4.65 mil­lion, In­dia is the world’s sec­ond-worst af­fected coun­try, trail­ing only the United States, which has over 6.4 mil­lion cases.</p>
    <p>But the growth in in­fec­tions in In­dia is faster than any­where else in the world, as cases surge through ur­ban and ru­ral ar­eas.</p>
    <p>The west­ern state of Ma­ha­rash­tra has been par­tic­u­larly hard hit, with to­tal con­firmed cases breach­ing the one mil­lion mark late on Fri­day, mak­ing it the first state or prov­ince any­where in the world to cross that mark.</p>
    <p>If the state, which is In­dia’s rich­est, were a coun­try, it would ri­val Rus­sia for the fourth-high­est num­ber of coro­n­avirus cases glob­ally.</p>
    <p>Mumbai, home to In­dia’s fi­nan­cial cen­tre and Bol­ly­wood moviemak­ing industry, is lo­cated in Ma­ha­rash­tra.</p>
    <p>Gov­ern­ment of­fi­cials and ex­perts said the un­abated rise in cases in Ma­ha­rash­tra and other parts of the coun­try was likely a result of eco­nomic ac­tiv­ity restart­ing, lo­cal fes­ti­vals and lock­down fa­tigue.</p>
    <p>“I am so dis­ap­pointed with the pan­demic sit­u­a­tion in In­dia,” Dr Bhra­mar Mukher­jee, a pro­fes­sor of bio­statis­tics and epi­demi­ol­ogy at the Univer­sity of Michi­gan, who has been track­ing In­dia’s Covid-19 sit­u­a­tion closely, said on Twit­ter.</p>
    <p>“It is get­ting worse and worse each week, but a large part of the na­tion seems to have made the choice to ig­nore this cri­sis.”</p>

